        <!-- Q1 -->
        <div class="section" id="q1">
            <h2 class="section-title">Q1: IEEE 802.3 Standard & MAC Sublayer</h2>
            
            <div class="section-content">
                <div class="content-subsection">
                    <h3><i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i> Overview of IEEE 802.3</h3>
                    <p>The <span class="highlight">IEEE 802.3 standard</span> defines comprehensive specifications for Ethernet networks, governing how data is transmitted across local area networks (LANs). This standard encompasses two critical layers of network communication.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-layer-group"></i> Core Layers Defined by IEEE 802.3</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Physical Layer:</strong> Specifies how data is converted into electrical signals and transmitted through physical media</li>
                        <li><strong>Data Link Layer (MAC Sublayer):</strong> Manages network access control and ensures orderly data transmission among multiple devices</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="content-subsection">
                    <h3><i class="fas fa-tasks"></i> MAC Sublayer: Function and Purpose</h3>
                    <p>The Media Access Control (MAC) sublayer serves as the traffic management system for Ethernet networks. It coordinates device access to the shared communication medium, preventing data collisions and ensuring fair network utilization.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="content-subsection">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-traffic-light"></i> CSMA/CD Protocol Framework</h4>
                    <p>The MAC sublayer implements <span class="highlight">CSMA/CD</span> (Carrier Sense Multiple Access with Collision Detection), a fundamental protocol that manages network access:</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-search"></i> Carrier Sense (CS)</h4>
                    <p>Devices monitor the network medium before transmission. Each device verifies that no other device is currently transmitting before initiating data transfer.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-users"></i> Multiple Access (MA)</h4>
                    <p>All devices share equal rights to network access. The protocol ensures equitable medium utilization without centralized control of transmission authority.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i> Collision Detection (CD)</h4>
                    <p>The system continuously monitors for simultaneous transmissions. When two devices transmit concurrently, the collision is immediately detected and both transmissions are terminated.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-cogs"></i> Collision Resolution Procedure</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Both transmitting devices immediately cease transmission upon collision detection</li>
                        <li>A jam signal is broadcast to notify all network devices of the collision event</li>
                        <li>Each device implements exponential backoff, waiting a random duration before retry</li>
                        <li>Transmission is attempted again after the random backoff interval</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Q2 -->
        <div class="section" id="q2">
            <h2 class="section-title">Q2: Ethernet Frame Structure</h2>
            
            <div class="section-content">
                <p style="font-size: 1.3em; color: #d0d0d0; margin-bottom: 25px;">The Ethernet frame consists of seven distinct components, each serving a specific function in reliable data delivery.</p>

                <div class="frame-visualization">
                    <div class="frame-field">
                        Preamble
                        <div class="tooltip">7 bytes - Synchronizes receiving stations</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="frame-field">
                        SFD
                        <div class="tooltip">1 byte - Start Frame Delimiter</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="frame-field">
                        Destination
                        <div class="tooltip">6 bytes - MAC address of destination</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="frame-field">
                        Source
                        <div class="tooltip">6 bytes - MAC address of source</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="frame-field">
                        Type/Length
                        <div class="tooltip">2 bytes - Protocol type or frame length</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="frame-field">
                        Data
                        <div class="tooltip">46-1500 bytes - Payload data</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="frame-field">
                        FCS
                        <div class="tooltip">4 bytes - Frame Check Sequence (CRC)</div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-sync-alt"></i> 1. Preamble (7 bytes)</h4>
                    <p><strong>Pattern:</strong> Binary sequence 10101010 repeated seven times</p>
                    <p><strong>Function:</strong> Enables receiver clock synchronization with sender timing</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-flag"></i> 2. Start Frame Delimiter (SFD) (1 byte)</h4>
                    <p><strong>Pattern:</strong> 10101011</p>
                    <p><strong>Function:</strong> Marks the definitive beginning of the data frame</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-location-arrow"></i> 3. Destination Address (6 bytes)</h4>
                    <p><strong>Content:</strong> 48-bit MAC address of the recipient device</p>
                    <p><strong>Example:</strong> 00:1A:2B:3C:4D:5E</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-user"></i> 4. Source Address (6 bytes)</h4>
                    <p><strong>Content:</strong> 48-bit MAC address of the transmitting device</p>
                    <p><strong>Example:</strong> A1:B2:C3:D4:E5:F6</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-ruler"></i> 5. Length/Type Field (2 bytes)</h4>
                    <p><strong>Content:</strong> Specifies either frame data length or protocol type</p>
                    <p><strong>Function:</strong> Enables receiver interpretation of frame content</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-database"></i> 6. Data and Padding (46-1500 bytes)</h4>
                    <p><strong>Content:</strong> Payload data from upper-layer protocols</p>
                    <p><strong>Minimum Length:</strong> 46 bytes (padding added if necessary)</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-shield-alt"></i> 7. Frame Check Sequence (CRC) (4 bytes)</h4>
                    <p><strong>Content:</strong> 32-bit cyclic redundancy check value</p>
                    <p><strong>Function:</strong> Enables detection of transmission errors</p>
                </div>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-info-circle"></i> Frame Structure Significance</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Minimum total frame size: 64 bytes (essential for collision detection)</li>
                        <li>Maximum frame size: 1518 bytes (including headers and CRC)</li>
                        <li>Preamble and SFD provide timing synchronization</li>
                        <li>CRC ensures data integrity verification</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Q3 -->
        <div class="section" id="q3">
            <h2 class="section-title">Q3: Physical vs Logical Topology</h2>
            
            <div class="section-content">
                <div class="content-subsection">
                    <h3><i class="fas fa-project-diagram"></i> Topology Classifications</h3>
                    <p>Network topology can be analyzed from two distinct perspectives: the physical arrangement of hardware and the logical flow of data communication. These perspectives often differ in modern Ethernet implementations.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-star"></i> Physical Topology: Star Configuration</h4>
                    <p><strong>Definition:</strong> The actual spatial arrangement of network devices and cabling</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Centralized connection architecture with dedicated links to each device</li>
                        <li>Enhanced reliability: individual device failures do not affect remaining network</li>
                        <li>Simplified troubleshooting and device addition procedures</li>
                        <li>Predominant topology in contemporary network deployments</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-bus"></i> Logical Topology: Bus Configuration</h4>
                    <p><strong>Definition:</strong> The conceptual path data follows through the network</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Data transmission occurs on a shared medium accessible to all devices</li>
                        <li>Broadcast transmissions reach all network participants simultaneously</li>
                        <li>CSMA/CD protocol assumes shared medium access model</li>
                        <li>Maintains backward compatibility with legacy Ethernet implementations</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> Topology Divergence Explanation</h4>
                    <p>Modern Ethernet networks employ physical star topology with central switches while maintaining logical bus topology semantics. This hybrid design achieves reliability benefits while preserving protocol compatibility.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Q4 -->
        <div class="section" id="q4">
            <h2 class="section-title">Q4: Addressing Types in Ethernet</h2>
            
            <div class="section-content">
                <div class="content-subsection">
                    <h3><i class="fas fa-address-card"></i> MAC Address Classification</h3>
                    <p>Ethernet supports three distinct addressing modes, each serving specific communication requirements within local area networks.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-user"></i> Unicast Addressing (One-to-One)</h4>
                    <p><strong>Definition:</strong> Communication between a single sender and single recipient</p>
                    <p><strong>Example MAC:</strong> 00:1A:2B:3C:4D:5E</p>
                    <p><strong>Identification:</strong> Last bit of first octet = 0</p>
                    <p><strong>Applications:</strong> Web browsing, email, file transfers</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-users"></i> Multicast Addressing (One-to-Many)</h4>
                    <p><strong>Definition:</strong> Communication from one sender to designated group</p>
                    <p><strong>Example MAC:</strong> 01:00:5E:00:00:01</p>
                    <p><strong>Identification:</strong> Last bit of first octet = 1</p>
                    <p><strong>Applications:</strong> Video streaming, live conferences, group distribution</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-globe"></i> Broadcast Addressing (One-to-All)</h4>
                    <p><strong>Definition:</strong> Communication from sender to all devices on network</p>
                    <p><strong>Example MAC:</strong> FF:FF:FF:FF:FF:FF</p>
                    <p><strong>Identification:</strong> All bits set to 1 (hexadecimal F)</p>
                    <p><strong>Applications:</strong> DHCP requests, ARP queries, network discovery</p>
                </div>

                <table class="data-table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Addressing Type</th>
                            <th>Recipient Count</th>
                            <th>Typical Use Case</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Unicast</strong></td>
                            <td>Single device</td>
                            <td>Web browsing, email, file transfer</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Multicast</strong></td>
                            <td>Specific group</td>
                            <td>Video streaming, multimedia conferencing</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Broadcast</strong></td>
                            <td>All devices</td>
                            <td>DHCP, ARP, network-wide announcements</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>
        </div>

