        <!-- Q6 -->
        <div class="section" id="q6">
            <h2 class="section-title">Q6: Standard Ethernet vs Switched Ethernet Architecture</h2>
            
            <div class="section-content">
                <div class="content-subsection">
                    <h3><i class="fas fa-balance-scale"></i> Comparative Analysis: Hubs and Switches</h3>
                    <p>The evolution from hub-based to switch-based architecture represents a fundamental advancement in network design. Both serve as connection points but operate according to distinctly different principles.</p>
                </div>

                <table class="data-table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Characteristic</th>
                            <th>Hub (Standard Ethernet)</th>
                            <th>Switch (Switched Ethernet)</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>OSI Layer</strong></td>
                            <td>Physical Layer (Layer 1)</td>
                            <td>Data Link Layer (Layer 2)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Intelligence Level</strong></td>
                            <td>Passive repeater device</td>
                            <td>Active forwarding device</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Forwarding Logic</strong></td>
                            <td>Broadcasts to all ports</td>
                            <td>Unicast to specific port</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Collision Behavior</strong></td>
                            <td>Frequent collisions</td>
                            <td>Eliminated through port isolation</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Bandwidth Distribution</strong></td>
                            <td>Shared equally</td>
                            <td>Dedicated per port</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Full-Duplex Operation</strong></td>
                            <td>Not supported</td>
                            <td>Fully supported</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>CSMA/CD Requirement</strong></td>
                            <td>Essential</td>
                            <td>Not required</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>

                <div class="content-subsection">
                    <h3><i class="fas fa-hub"></i> Hub Operating Principle</h3>
                    <p>Network hubs function as simple repeater devices at the physical layer. When receiving data on one port, hubs amplify and retransmit the signal to all other ports simultaneously.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-exclamation-circle"></i> Hub Limitations</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Entire network bandwidth shared across all connected devices</li>
                        <li>All devices exist in single collision domain</li>
                        <li>Frequent collision events require CSMA/CD resolution</li>
                        <li>Performance degradation with additional network users</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="content-subsection">
                    <h3><i class="fas fa-switch"></i> Switch Operating Principle</h3>
                    <p>Network switches operate intelligently at the data link layer, making forwarding decisions based on destination MAC addresses. Switches maintain dynamic MAC address tables enabling intelligent frame delivery.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> Switch Advantages</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Each port constitutes independent collision domain</li>
                        <li>Dedicated bandwidth available to each connected device</li>
                        <li>Full-duplex communication eliminates collision possibility</li>
                        <li>MAC address learning enables intelligent forwarding</li>
                        <li>Scalable architecture supporting network growth</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="content-subsection">
                    <h3><i class="fas fa-rocket"></i> Performance Enhancement Mechanisms</h3>
                </div>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-sitemap"></i> Microsegmentation</h4>
                    <p>Each switch port represents an independent collision domain, eliminating shared medium contention and allowing simultaneous transmission across multiple ports.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-arrows-alt-h"></i> Full-Duplex Communication</h4>
                    <p>Switched networks enable simultaneous sending and receiving on each port, effectively doubling available bandwidth compared to shared hub architectures.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-hdd"></i> Intelligent Buffering</h4>
                    <p>Switches employ memory buffers to temporarily store frames when destination ports are busy, ensuring reliable delivery and eliminating data loss.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="info-card">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-chart-bar"></i> Performance Comparison Example</h4>
                    <p><strong>Hub-Based Network (10 devices):</strong> 100 Mbps shared = ~10 Mbps per device</p>
                    <p><strong>Switch-Based Network (10 devices):</strong> 100 Mbps per port × 10 = 1000 Mbps total capacity with full 100 Mbps dedicated per device</p>
                </div>

                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4><i class="fas fa-building"></i> Contemporary Network Architecture</h4>
                    <p>Network switches have become the universal standard for modern Ethernet implementations. Hub technology is considered obsolete. All modern deployments should utilize switches to ensure optimal performance, scalability, and reliability.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        function switchSection(sectionId, element) {
            // Hide all sections
            const sections = document.querySelectorAll('.section');
            sections.forEach(section => {
                section.classList.remove('active');
            });

            // Show selected section
            const targetSection = document.getElementById(sectionId);
            if (targetSection) {
                targetSection.classList.add('active');
                window.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior: 'smooth' });
            }

            // Update nav buttons
            const navLinks = document.querySelectorAll('.nav-link');
            navLinks.forEach(link => {
                link.classList.remove('active');
            });
            element.classList.add('active');
        }

        // Keyboard navigation
        document.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
            if (e.key === 'Home') {
                const homeBtn = document.querySelectorAll('.nav-link')[0];
                switchSection('intro', homeBtn);
            }
        });

        // Add animation to cards when they come into view
        const observerOptions = {
            threshold: 0.1,
            rootMargin: '0px 0px -50px 0px'
        };
        
        const observer = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {
            entries.forEach(entry => {
                if (entry.isIntersecting) {
                    entry.target.style.opacity = '1';
                    entry.target.style.transform = 'translateY(0)';
                }
            });
        }, observerOptions);
        
        // Observe all cards for animation
        document.querySelectorAll('.info-card, .highlight-box, .team-member').forEach(card => {
            card.style.opacity = '0';
            card.style.transform = 'translateY(20px)';
            card.style.transition = 'opacity 0.5s ease, transform 0.5s ease';
            observer.observe(card);
        });
    </script>
